            <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s3">
             <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Meanwhile, the n=
ext day, the <i>Times </i>published a story perhaps more germane to Lewis=
=E2=80=99s future at the <i>Post</i>. Central to Lewis=E2=80=99s strategy i=
s the creation of that =E2=80=9Cthird newsroom=E2=80=9D focused on =E2=80=
=9Csocial media journalism,=E2=80=9D servicing audiences on TikTok and Inst=
agram and X who rarely if ever engage with the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s owned =
and operated platforms. And yet, the <i>Times </i>had found that The News M=
ovement, the Gen Z-targeted social media company that Lewis had launched th=
ree years earlier, lost millions of dollars in 2023, slashed staff, and dra=
stically reduced revenue projections, and is now in talks to sell a majorit=
y stake to a Greek media company with Saudi backing. As the <i>Times </i>no=
ted, =E2=80=9CThe News Movement may provide a cautionary tale about how dif=
ficult it is to make money from the oceans of viewers who consume
news on social media platforms like TikTok and Instagram.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/=
>If you go back further in Lewis=E2=80=99s history, there are similar quest=
ions around his attempt as editor of the <i>Telegraph </i>to launch a stand=
-alone digital growth division known as =E2=80=9CProject Euston,=E2=80=9D i=
n 2009. The project, another precursor to the =E2=80=9Cthird newsroom,=E2=
=80=9D shuttered after he left the company six months later. Indeed, if the=
re=E2=80=99s one revelation I=E2=80=99ve gathered from all my conversations=
 with <i>Post </i>staffers in recent months, it=E2=80=99s that the skeptica=
l murmuring surrounding Lewis=E2=80=99s ethics actually belies a deeper and=
 more pervasive anxiety about his ability to lead the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s=
 business out of its current morass=E2=80=94<i>not </i>because he=E2=80=99s=
 lost the trust of some people for what he might have done as a journalist,=
 but because they=E2=80=99re still not convinced he actually knows what he=
=E2=80=99s doing as a media executive.<br/><br/>I=E2=80=99m not Freud, but =
I suspect something larger and no less
tumultuous is going on here. It=E2=80=99s very possible that Lewis has been=
 unclear about his plan for the third newsroom because the guy he picked to=
 run it, <b>Matt Murray</b>, is now running the main newsgathering outfit a=
nd seems to like it. Furthermore, this third newsroom sure seems likely to =
require a drastic reorganization of the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s non-core cove=
rage areas, which is likely to manifest only through meaningful layoffs, le=
adership changes, and possible M&amp;A=E2=80=94gory details that Lewis migh=
t be inclined to keep within the c-suite since he only recently regained fo=
oting on <i>terra firma</i>. And he is probably less concerned by the strat=
egic concerns of the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s newsroom than the validation of =
its owner, who ratified the plan.  <br/><br/>And while all of this <i>might=
 </i>understandably scare the shit out of his newsroom=E2=80=94the first, s=
econd, <i>and</i> third=E2=80=94there is a silver lining. If you=E2=80=99d =
told <b>David Sanger </b>or <b>Tom Friedman </b>back in 2014
that their beloved <i>Times </i>would morph into a recipe database, podcast=
 hub, sports news platform, goofy games module, and consumer retail player =
in a mere decade, I have little doubt that they would have marched into <b>=
Arthur Sulzberger</b>=E2=80=99s office and thrown a glass of his family=E2=
=80=99s favorite bitter iced tea in his face. And yet, <i>voil=C3=A0</i>, t=
hose plans were enacted <i>around </i>the core report without great foresha=
dowing, the <i>Times</i>=E2=80=99 newsroom never lost focus, and the Times =
Company, now worth $8.5 billion, is trading near a five-year high on the NY=
SE.<br/><br/>One can only imagine that Lewis, Bezos, and Stonesifer harbor =
similarly ambitious plans for the <i>Post</i>. Bezos, after all, has unlimi=
ted wealth and appetite and self-confidence. The tragedy of this recent cha=
pter in the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s history is that it undercuts the size of =
the opportunity. One hopes that a <i>Kumbaya </i>is around the corner.<br/>=
<br/>In any event, the anxieties at the
<i>Post </i>persist, despite the distractions of the campaign season and th=
e relatively calming presence of Murray. Lewis has said he plans to hire a =
new editor this year, but <i>Post </i>sources increasingly believe (or at l=
east hope) that he will keep Murray in the position. Whatever his intention=
s, the decision, once slated to be made before the end of summer, now seems=
 likely to be delayed until after the election. Indeed, I=E2=80=99m told th=
ey haven=E2=80=99t started interviews yet (why leave Provence?). In any cas=
e, barring the findings of Brown=E2=80=99s hoped-for criminal investigation=
, that will still be Lewis=E2=80=99s decision to make.<br/></td>
